Today, we're building on our number knowledge and learning how to say numbers above 100 in German! This is where things get a little interesting, especially with the "ones" and "tens" places.



âœ… ğ‡ğ¨ğ° ğ­ğ¨ ğŸğ¨ğ«ğ¦ ğğ®ğ¦ğ›ğğ«ğ¬ ğšğ›ğ¨ğ¯ğ ğŸğŸğŸ: The basic structure for numbers above 100 is: hundreds + one-digit/two-digit number. For two-digit numbers (21-99), German reverses the order of the tens and ones place: ones + und (and) + tens.



